<title>UK: UK March global trade gap 671 mln stg.</title>
<headline>UK March global trade gap 671 mln stg.</headline>
<dateline>LONDON 1997-05-29</dateline>
<text>
<p>The Office for National Statistics issued the following data on Britain's global trade in March (in million stg, previously announced data in brackets):</p>
<p>    GLOBAL TRADE		March   February	   March 96</p>
<p>    Trade balance	     -671    -771    (-758)   -1,067</p>
<p>    Exports		    13,643   14,011 (14,164)  13,746</p>
<p>    Imports		    14,314   14,782 (14,922)  14,813</p>
<p>    EU trade balance	    -20     -290   (-321)    -274</p>
<p>    EU exports		  7,929    7,850  (7,966)   7,967</p>
<p>    EU imports		  7,949    8,140  (8,287)   8,241</p>
<p>The erratic pattern of the deficit makes estimation of a trend difficult, the ONS said, but latest data suggest the whole world goods deficit is narrowing.  </p>
<p>    TRADE VALUE EX OIL/ERRATICS    March    February</p>
<p>    Trade balance (in million stg)    -1,297    -1,346  (-1,343)</p>
<p>    Latest qtr on pvs qtr (imports) -2.5%   -1.5    (-1.0%)</p>
<p>    Latest qtr on pvs qtr (exports)  UNCH   -1.5    (-1.0%)</p>
<p>TRADE VOLUME EX OIL/ERRATICS</p>
<p>    Import volume index (base 1990) 127.4   131.5  (132.7)</p>
<p>    Export volume index (base 1990) 141.5   144.7  (146.0)</p>
<p>    Latest qtr on pvs qtr (imports) unch     1.5%  (1.5%)</p>
<p>    Latest qtr on yr-ago qtr (imp)  3.5%     6.0%  (6.0%)</p>
<p>    Latest qtr on pvs qtr (exports) 2.0%     0.5%  (1.0%)</p>
<p>    Latest qtr on yr-ago qtr (exps) 6.5%     7.0%  (7.0%)</p>
<p>TRADE IN OIL (VALUE MLN STG)</p>
<p>    BALANCE				  604     443   (480)</p>
<p>    EXPORTS				  960     860   (896)</p>
<p>    IMPORTS				  356     417   (416)</p>
<p>The Reuters consensus forecast was for a March global trade deficit of around 900 million stg.</p>
<p>The March estimates show both export and import prices fell half a percent compared with February.</p>
<p>In the three months to March, export prices fell one percent and import prices fell one and a half percent. This led to an increase in the terms of trade, the ONS said.</p>
